# CodeBridge — Core Project Rules

## Architecture First

Before planning or implementing ANY feature:
1. Read `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` to understand the system design
2. Verify your approach aligns with the documented architecture
3. If you need to deviate, update the architecture doc AND log the change in `docs/change_log.md`

## Change Log Protocol

Any change to architecture, design decisions, or tech stack MUST be logged:
- File: `docs/change_log.md`
- Format: `| YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM | What Changed | Why | Section Affected |`
- Log BEFORE making the change, not after

## Run Log Protocol

Every test run, smoke test, build attempt, or deployment attempt:
- File: `docs/run_log.md`
- Format: `| YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM | Command | Result (pass/fail) | Notes |`
- Include the actual command run and its exit code

## Progress Tracking

Maintain `docs/progress.md` with current state at all times:
- What's done, what's in progress, what's blocked
- Update after completing each task
- This file is your memory across sessions — treat it as ground truth

## Get Shit Done Methodology

1. Ship working code, not perfect code — iterate
2. Never spend more than 30 minutes stuck on one problem — escalate or pivot
3. Use open-source packages per the architecture doc — don't reinvent
4. Every PR/commit must move toward a demoable feature
5. If it's not in the MVP P0 list, it waits

## Git Identity — HARD RULE

**Every commit MUST use the project owner's identity. No exceptions.**

Before EVERY git commit or push:
1. Verify: `git config user.name` must be `IndarKarhana`
2. Verify: `git config user.email` must be `ishukarhana@gmail.com`
3. If either is wrong, fix it FIRST: `git config user.name "IndarKarhana" && git config user.email "ishukarhana@gmail.com"`
4. After every commit, run: `git log -1 --format='%an <%ae>'` to confirm author
5. NEVER skip this check. NEVER allow "cursor", "assistant", "bot", or any AI-related author name
6. If a commit was made with wrong identity, amend it immediately before pushing

This is non-negotiable. The hackathon submission must show the developer as the author.

## Auto-Commit on Success

After every successful milestone (feature working, build passing, test passing, deployment succeeding):
1. Stage all relevant changes
2. Commit with a descriptive message following conventional commits (feat:, fix:, chore:, docs:)
3. Verify author with `git log -1 --format='%an <%ae>'`
4. Push to origin
5. Log the commit in `docs/progress.md` under the completed section

A "milestone" means: something that was broken/missing now works. Don't batch — commit often.

## Code Quality Standards

- Type everything (TypeScript strict mode, Python type hints)
- No `any` types in TypeScript, no untyped functions in Python
- Every function has a clear single responsibility
- Error handling is required — no silent failures
- Pydantic models for all data crossing agent boundaries
